        "answer": "Where Rust in Peace demanded relentless double-bass blasting, blistering tempos, and dense jazz-influenced fills, Countdown to Extinction asked Menza to pull back and serve the songs. His playing on tracks like \"Symphony of Destruction\" and \"Foreclosure of a Dream\" relies on mid-tempo pocket discipline, deliberate hi-hat pulse work, and concise melodic fills rather than constant technical flurries. \"Sweating Bullets\" lets his jazz background surface openly with a shuffled hi-hat and ride feel that no other Megadeth track displays as clearly. The restraint required for that pivot is, in many ways, harder than executing the Rust in Peace material."
